-COL
In bootstrap grids, 'col' are the coloumns. Rows are 12 col big.
So, col-lg-6 and col-lg-6 would take up a whole row.

-lg, md , sm 
These are going to be the layouts you want the coloumns to interact with. Or display.
For example, on desktop/laptop lg is used to contorl the coloumns. For example:

class="col-md-12" (this takes up the entire row)

md is used for tablets. So if you want a coloumn to react when it hits a tablet size
you'd use md. 

sm is used for mobile devices. So for example:

class"col-sm-6" <----- now it is set up to react when the screen gets to a mobile
device size. but it is only taking up 50% because of the "6".




<div class="row">
    <div class="col-lg-3 col-md-4 col-sm-6" style="background-color:yellow; border: 1px solid">
        4
    </div>
        <div class="col-lg-3 col-md-4 col-sm-6" style="background-color:red; border: 1px solid">
        4
    </div>
        <div class="col-lg-3 col-md-4 col-sm-6" style="background-color:blue; border: 1px solid">
        4
    </div>
            <div class="col-lg-3 col-md-4 col-sm-6" style="background-color:blue; border: 1px solid">
        4
    </div>
</div>